Certainly! Below is an example of how you might convert the handwritten notes into a simple HTML/JS webpage. This code will create a webpage with a title, a paragraph, and a button that changes the text when clicked. The text in the image is used as an example, but you can replace it with your own content.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My Joke Website</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .container {
            text-align: center;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        .button {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
            margin: 10px;
        }
        .button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>My Joke Website</h1>
        <p>Really funny joke 1</p>
        <p>Especially if you're a bot</p>
        <button onclick="changeText()">Click me</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        function changeText() {
            const text1 = document.getElementById("text1");
            const text2 = document.getElementById("text2");
            const button = document.getElementById("button");

            if (text1.innerHTML === "Really funny joke 1") {
                text1.innerHTML = "Especially if you're a bot";
                text2.innerHTML = "Really funny joke 2";
                button.innerHTML = "Click me";
            } else {
                text1.innerHTML = "Really funny joke 2";
                text2.innerHTML = "Especially if you're a bot";
                button.innerHTML = "Click me";
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code will create a webpage with a title, a paragraph, and a button. When the button is clicked, the text in the paragraphs will switch between the two examples provided in the image. You can customize the text and the behavior of the button to suit your needs.

Certainly! Below is a simple HTML/JavaScript code snippet that can be used to create a basic joke submission form similar to the one in the image. This code will create a simple webpage with a text area for the joke and a button to submit the joke. When the button is clicked, the joke will be displayed in a new div.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Joke Submission Form</title>
<style>
  body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  }
  .form-container {
    width: 300px;
    margin: auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #000;
  }
  .form-container input[type="text"] {
    width: 100%;
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .form-container button {
    padding: 10px 20px;
    margin-top: 10px;
    background-color: #007bff;
    color: white;
    border: none;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  .joke-container {
    margin-top: 20px;
  }
  .joke-container p {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="form-container">
  <input type="text" id="joke-input" placeholder="Enter your joke here">
  <button onclick="submitJoke()">Submit Joke</button>
</div>

<div class="joke-container" id="joke-container">
  <!-- Joke will be displayed here -->
</div>

<script>
  function submitJoke() {
    const jokeInput = document.getElementById("joke-input");
    const jokeContainer = document.getElementById("joke-container");

    if (jokeInput.value.trim() !== "") {
      jokeContainer.innerHTML = jokeInput.value;
      jokeInput.value = "";
    }
  }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This code will create a simple webpage with a text area for the joke and a button to submit the joke. When the button is clicked, the joke will be displayed in a new div. The joke will be replaced with a new joke each time the button is clicked.

Please note that this is a very basic example and does not include any backend functionality to store or retrieve the jokes. It also does not include any validation or error handling. For a fully functional joke submission system, you would need to implement additional features such as user authentication, joke validation, and possibly a database to store the jokes.
